table abc_extra186.abc_abcmeta_init_new_qualnames:
  description: "abc.ABCMeta __init__ and __new__ qualname identity in abcabcmeta186 namespace — ABCMeta.__init__.__qualname__=='type.__init__' (len=13: 'type'=4+'.'=1+'__init__'=8=13; ABCMeta does NOT override __init__ — it inherits type.__init__ directly; the qualname 'type.__init__' reveals the ACTUAL defining class is 'type', not ABCMeta; this is a critical distinction: qualname traces to the defining class, not the accessing class); ABCMeta.__new__.__qualname__=='ABCMeta.__new__' (len=15: 'ABCMeta'=7+'.'=1+'__new__'=7=15; ABCMeta DOES override __new__ — this is where ABCMeta sets up the internal abstract method tracking (_abc_data) via the C extension _abc module); 'type.__init__'=13 < 'ABCMeta.__new__'=15 < 'ABCMeta.register'=16; the shorter __init__ qualname (inheriting from type) vs the longer __new__ qualname (defined on ABCMeta itself) reveals which methods ABCMeta defines vs inherits; verified with Python 3.14.3"
  kind: python_call_eq
  category: identity
  id_prefix: abcabcmeta186

  columns: [id, function, args, expected, description]
  rows:
    - ["init_qualname_eq",  "ABCMeta.__init__.__qualname__.__eq__",  ["type.__init__"],    true, "abc.ABCMeta.__init__.__qualname__ == 'type.__init__' (len=13; ABCMeta inherits __init__ from type, not overriding it; qualname reveals defining class is 'type'); verified Python 3.14.3"]
    - ["init_qualname_len", "ABCMeta.__init__.__qualname__.__len__", [],                   13,   "abc.ABCMeta.__init__.__qualname__.__len__() == 13 ('type.__init__'=13: 'type'=4+'.'=1+'__init__'=8=13; shorter than ABCMeta.__new__ qualname=15); verified Python 3.14.3"]
    - ["new_qualname_eq",   "ABCMeta.__new__.__qualname__.__eq__",   ["ABCMeta.__new__"],  true, "abc.ABCMeta.__new__.__qualname__ == 'ABCMeta.__new__' (len=15; ABCMeta overrides __new__ to set up _abc_data via _abc C extension); verified Python 3.14.3"]
    - ["new_qualname_len",  "ABCMeta.__new__.__qualname__.__len__",  [],                   15,   "abc.ABCMeta.__new__.__qualname__.__len__() == 15 ('ABCMeta.__new__'=15: 'ABCMeta'=7+'.'=1+'__new__'=7=15); __new__(15) > __init__(13) by 2; register(16) > __new__(15) by 1; verified Python 3.14.3"]
    - ["init_lt_new",       "ABCMeta.__init__.__qualname__.__len__", [],                   13,   "ABCMeta.__init__ qualname (13) < ABCMeta.__new__ qualname (15): __init__ is inherited from type (shorter prefix 'type') while __new__ is defined on ABCMeta (longer prefix 'ABCMeta'); verified Python 3.14.3"]

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Standalone invariants — abc_extra186
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

invariant abc_extra186.abc_ABCMeta_name_eq:
  description: "abc.ABCMeta.__name__.__eq__('ABCMeta') returns True — ABCMeta is the metaclass that enables the Abstract Base Class (ABC) pattern in Python; ABCMeta.__name__=='ABCMeta' (len=7: A(1)B(2)C(3)M(4)e(5)t(6)a(7)); 'ABCMeta'=7 compounds 'ABC'=3 (Abstract Base Class acronym) + 'Meta'=4 (metaclass suffix); ABCMeta is used as metaclass=ABCMeta in class definitions to enable @abstractmethod enforcement — Python raises TypeError if a subclass of an ABC fails to implement all abstract methods; the more common modern pattern is class MyABC(ABC): which uses abc.ABC (which itself uses ABCMeta as its metaclass); ABCMeta.__name__='ABCMeta'=7 is the same length as abc.ABCMeta.__name__ checks established in earlier abc specs; NEW in extra186: first standalone ABCMeta.__name__ invariant in abcabcmeta186 namespace; verified with Python 3.14.3 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-11"
  category: identity
  kind: python_call_eq
  function: ABCMeta.__name__.__eq__
  args: ["ABCMeta"]
  expected: true

invariant abc_extra186.abc_ABCMeta_module_eq:
  description: "abc.ABCMeta.__module__.__eq__('abc') returns True — ABCMeta.__module__=='abc' (len=3: a(1)b(2)c(3)); ABCMeta is defined directly in Lib/abc.py at the top level; 'abc'=3 is the shortest module path across all 4 specs in this group: abc(3) < asyncio.queues(14) < multiprocessing.queues(22) < concurrent.futures._base(24); 'abc' is also one of the shortest module paths in the entire stdlib — only built-in module names like 'io', 're', 'os', 'gc' are shorter; the brevity of the module name reflects the abc module's fundamental role: abstract base classes are a core Python metaprogramming concept given a dedicated short-named module; NEW in extra186: standalone ABCMeta.__module__ invariant confirming the module name length is 3; verified with Python 3.14.3 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-11"
  category: identity
  kind: python_call_eq
  function: ABCMeta.__module__.__eq__
  args: ["abc"]
  expected: true

invariant abc_extra186.abc_ABCMeta_base_is_type:
  description: "abc.ABCMeta.__bases__[0].__name__.__eq__('type') returns True — ABCMeta.__bases__[0].__name__=='type' (len=4: t(1)y(2)p(3)e(4)); ABCMeta is a metaclass and therefore a subclass of 'type' (the root metaclass); type is the class whose instances are class objects — by inheriting from type, ABCMeta makes ABCMeta instances (like abc.ABC and user-defined ABCs) into valid Python classes; ABCMeta overrides __new__ (to set up abstract tracking) and both __instancecheck__ and __subclasscheck__ (to consult the virtual subclass registry); 'type'=4 is shorter than 'ABCMeta'=7; the inheritance type → ABCMeta enables the metaclass to intercept isinstance() and issubclass() calls on any class using ABCMeta as its metaclass; contrast: asyncio.Queue.__bases__[0].__name__=='_LoopBoundMixin' (15), multiprocessing.queues.Queue.__bases__[0].__name__=='object' (6), concurrent.futures.Future.__bases__[0].__name__=='object' (6); only ABCMeta inherits from 'type' among these 4 specs; NEW in extra186: standalone ABCMeta.__bases__[0].__name__ invariant; verified with Python 3.14.3 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-11"
  category: identity
  kind: python_call_eq
  function: "ABCMeta.__bases__[0].__name__.__eq__"
  args: ["type"]
  expected: true

invariant abc_extra186.abc_ABCMeta_register_qualname_eq:
  description: "abc.ABCMeta.register.__qualname__.__eq__('ABCMeta.register') returns True — ABCMeta.register.__qualname__=='ABCMeta.register' (len=16: 'ABCMeta'=7+'.'=1+'register'=8=16); register(cls) adds cls to the ABC's virtual subclass registry so that isinstance(instance, MyABC) returns True for instances of cls even if cls does not inherit from MyABC; register() does NOT require cls to implement any abstract methods — it is purely a registry declaration; registered classes appear in the __subclasses__ list returned by the ABC's __subclasshook__; register(16) < __subclasscheck__==__instancecheck__(25) by 9; 'register'=8 is the longest non-dunder method name in the ABCMeta public API; NEW in extra186: standalone ABCMeta.register.__qualname__ invariant in abcabcmeta186 namespace; verified with Python 3.14.3 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-11"
  category: identity
  kind: python_call_eq
  function: ABCMeta.register.__qualname__.__eq__
  args: ["ABCMeta.register"]
  expected: true

invariant abc_extra186.abc_ABCMeta_subclasscheck_qualname_eq:
  description: "abc.ABCMeta.__subclasscheck__.__qualname__.__eq__('ABCMeta.__subclasscheck__') returns True — ABCMeta.__subclasscheck__.__qualname__=='ABCMeta.__subclasscheck__' (len=25: 'ABCMeta'=7+'.'=1+'__subclasscheck__'=17=25); __subclasscheck__ is called by issubclass(C, ABC) — ABCMeta overrides type.__subclasscheck__ to: (1) call ABC.__subclasshook__(C) first, (2) if NotImplemented consult the virtual subclass registry, (3) fall back to standard type-based issubclass; '__subclasscheck__'=17 chars is the longest method name in the ABCMeta public API; __subclasscheck__==__instancecheck__ at qualname length 25 — a 2-way tie that reflects the symmetric override of both isinstance and issubclass hooks; NEW in extra186: standalone ABCMeta.__subclasscheck__.__qualname__ invariant; verified with Python 3.14.3 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-11"
  category: identity
  kind: python_call_eq
  function: "ABCMeta.__subclasscheck__.__qualname__.__eq__"
  args: ["ABCMeta.__subclasscheck__"]
  expected: true

invariant abc_extra186.abc_ABCMeta_instancecheck_qualname_eq:
  description: "abc.ABCMeta.__instancecheck__.__qualname__.__eq__('ABCMeta.__instancecheck__') returns True — ABCMeta.__instancecheck__.__qualname__=='ABCMeta.__instancecheck__' (len=25: 'ABCMeta'=7+'.'=1+'__instancecheck__'=17=25); __instancecheck__ is called by isinstance(obj, ABC) — ABCMeta overrides type.__instancecheck__ to consult the ABC registry and __subclasshook__; '__instancecheck__'=17 chars == '__subclasscheck__'=17 chars: a 2-way tie at the method level (both have the same number of characters); at the qualname level: 'ABCMeta.__instancecheck__'=25 == 'ABCMeta.__subclasscheck__'=25 — still tied; __instancecheck__(25) == __subclasscheck__(25) > register(16) > __new__(15) > __init__(13); NEW in extra186: standalone ABCMeta.__instancecheck__.__qualname__ invariant completing the symmetric pair; verified with Python 3.14.3 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-11"
  category: identity
  kind: python_call_eq
  function: "ABCMeta.__instancecheck__.__qualname__.__eq__"
  args: ["ABCMeta.__instancecheck__"]
  expected: true

invariant abc_extra186.abc_ABCMeta_init_qualname_eq:
  description: "abc.ABCMeta.__init__.__qualname__.__eq__('type.__init__') returns True — ABCMeta.__init__.__qualname__=='type.__init__' (len=13: 'type'=4+'.'=1+'__init__'=8=13); the qualname 'type.__init__' (not 'ABCMeta.__init__') reveals that ABCMeta does NOT define its own __init__ — it inherits __init__ from 'type' without overriding; this means type.__init__ is called when constructing a new ABCMeta class (which happens during class body execution for any class using ABCMeta as metaclass); contrast with ABCMeta.__new__ where qualname IS 'ABCMeta.__new__' (ABCMeta does override __new__ to set up _abc_data); the inherited __init__ qualname pattern (prefix is 'type' not 'ABCMeta') is a reliable signal that the method is NOT overridden on ABCMeta; 'type.__init__'=13 is shorter than 'ABCMeta.__new__'=15 by 2 because 'type'=4 < 'ABCMeta'=7 (shorter prefix); NEW in extra186: standalone ABCMeta.__init__.__qualname__ invariant; verified with Python 3.14.3 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-11"
  category: identity
  kind: python_call_eq
  function: "ABCMeta.__init__.__qualname__.__eq__"
  args: ["type.__init__"]
  expected: true

invariant abc_extra186.abc_ABCMeta_new_qualname_eq:
  description: "abc.ABCMeta.__new__.__qualname__.__eq__('ABCMeta.__new__') returns True — ABCMeta.__new__.__qualname__=='ABCMeta.__new__' (len=15: 'ABCMeta'=7+'.'=1+'__new__'=7=15); the qualname 'ABCMeta.__new__' (prefix IS 'ABCMeta') reveals that ABCMeta DOES define its own __new__ — contrast with __init__ whose qualname 'type.__init__' reveals inheritance from type; ABCMeta.__new__ is responsible for: setting up the _abc_data descriptor (via the C _abc module) that tracks abstract methods and registered virtual subclasses; calling type.__new__ to create the class object; establishing the ABC machinery before any instance of the metaclass (i.e., any ABC class) is returned; '__new__'=7 chars == 'ABCMeta'=7 chars: the method name has the same length as the class name (coincidence); 'ABCMeta.__new__'=15 < 'ABCMeta.register'=16 by 1; NEW in extra186: standalone ABCMeta.__new__.__qualname__ invariant completing the 8-method coverage for abc.ABCMeta; verified with Python 3.14.3 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-11"
  category: identity
  kind: python_call_eq
  function: "ABCMeta.__new__.__qualname__.__eq__"
  args: ["ABCMeta.__new__"]
  expected: true
